Creating a simple movie website involves a combination of HTML, CSS, and potentially JavaScript. Below is a basic example of a movie website. This code includes the structure of the site using HTML, some styling using CSS, and includes a section where you can add movie titles, descriptions, and images.

### HTML (index.html)

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>My Movie Website</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <header>
        <h1>Welcome to My Movie Website</h1>
        <nav>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="#movies">Movies</a></li>
                <li><a href="#about">About</a></li>
                <li><a href="#contact">Contact</a></li>
            </ul>
        </nav>
    </header>

    <main>
        <section id="movies">
            <h2>Featured Movies</h2>
            <div class="movie">
                <h3>Movie Title 1</h3>
                <img src="movie1.jpg" alt="Movie Title 1" />
                <p>Description of Movie Title 1 goes here. Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movie">
                <h3>Movie Title 2</h3>
                <img src="movie2.jpg" alt="Movie Title 2" />
                <p>Description of Movie Title 2 goes here. Donec vel risus commodo, pellentesque metus eu, iaculis turpis.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movie">
                <h3>Movie Title 3</h3>
                <img src="movie3.jpg" alt="Movie Title 3" />
                <p>Description of Movie Title 3 goes here. Integer at nisi id odio fermentum ultrices.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="about">
            <h2>About</h2>
            <p>This is a simple movie website created to showcase my favorite films. Stay tuned for more updates!</p>
        </section>

        <section id="contact">
            <h2>Contact</h2>
            <p>If you would like to reach out, please email me at: <a href="mailto:example@example.com">example@example.com</a></p>
        </section>
    </main>

    <footer>
        <p>&copy; 2023 My Movie Website</p>
    </footer>
</body>
</html>
```

### CSS (styles.css)

```css
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
}

header {
    background: #333;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 10px 0;
}

header h1 {
    text-align: center;
}

nav ul {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
}

nav ul li {
    display: inline;
    margin: 0 15px;
}

nav a {
    color: #fff;
    text-decoration: none;
}

main {
    padding: 20px;
}

section {
    margin-bottom: 40px;
}

.movie {
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    border-radius: 5px;
    padding: 15px;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
    text-align: center;
}

.movie img {
    max-width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border-radius: 5px;
}

footer {
    text-align: center;
    padding: 10px 0;
    background: #333;
    color: white;
    position: relative;
    bottom: 0;
    width: 100%;
}
```

### Usage

1. **Create**, or ensure you have these two files in a folder:
   - `index.html`
   - `styles.css`
   
2. **Add images** named `movie1.jpg`, `movie2.jpg`, and `movie3.jpg` in the same folder (you can replace these with your own movie images).

3. **Open** `index.html` in a web browser to view your simple movie website.

### Additional Features
For a more advanced website, consider adding:
- A JavaScript function to dynamically load movies.
- A backend to store and manage a movie database.
- Responsive design using CSS frameworks like Bootstrap or media queries for mobile compatibility.
- Integration with APIs for real movie data, like The Movie Database (TMDb) API. 

This template should serve as a good starting point!